subSubSection.paragraph:
Antennae. Ant. I with seven chaetae, of which three dorsal ciliated mac (
Fig. 15
); Ant. II with eleven chaetae, of which three ciliated mac dorsally. Ant. III sensorial organ with two thickened ms in a cuticular fold; two guard S straight, Sgv as thick as and 20–25% longer than Sgd, and thinner and longer than Ant. IV S1–S8 (
Fig. 18
); one ventro-external ms more basally. Ant. IV with S1-S8 thick, strongly bent and subequal (
Fig. 18
).

Ocelli 2 + 2 without pigment, located on the edges of tubercle Oc (
Fig. 15
). Mandibles thin, bidentate; maxilla heads styliform. Labium long with four basal chaetae (E,F,G,f with F very long), three distal chaetae (A,C,D) with one or possibly two minute x-papillae, and three lateral chaetae (c,d,e) (
Fig. 16
). Labrum ogival, rounded apically (
Fig. 17
); labral formula 0/2,4.

Postcephalic chaetotaxy and tubercles (
Table 3B
and 
Figs 20–23
). Chaetae Di1, 2, 3 not on a line on Th. II–III, Di1 being clearly external to the line Di2–Di3; Di3 as a mic, much shorter than Di2 (
Fig. 20
). Chaetae Di2 posterointernal to Di1 on Abd. I–IV. Chaetal group Di of Abd. IV at the same level as De and DL. Tubercles Di of Abd. V closely adjacent, but not fused across the midline, their anterior mes (Di2) less distant than Di1 mac (
Fig 23
).
